+# Scout agent rules
+
+Scout is an evidence-first research engine evolving into an eval-gated, self-improving problem-solving agent platform.
+
+Use the Ponytail ladder before writing code:
+
+1. Does this need to exist? If not, do not build it.
+2. Does this already exist in Scout? Reuse the existing helper/module.
+3. Does the standard library or platform already solve it?
+4. Does an installed dependency already solve it?
+5. Can this be one line?
+6. Only then write the minimum code that works.
+
+Project-specific rules:
+
+- Harness before feature: add or update eval coverage before changing behavior.
+- Deterministic-first, model-second: use hard routing/ranking rules before adding model calls.
+- Keep route handlers thin; shared logic belongs in small helpers.
+- Do not add dependencies unless the existing stack cannot cover the task.
+- Do not silently weaken evidence, grounding, memory isolation, security, or budget checks.
+- New agent/swarm/caching/reranker paths must be flag-gated and default off.
+- Memory writes must stay scoped and traceable; durable facts need provenance.
+- Non-trivial logic needs one runnable check or eval case.
+
+For the platform roadmap, implement milestones from `docs/SCOUT_PLATFORM_PLAN.md` in order:
+
+```text
+M0 measurement -> M1 provider guard -> M2 parallel/streaming -> M3 intent -> M4 memory -> M5 retrieval/rerank -> M6 cache -> M8 sandbox -> M7 executor -> M9 self-learning
+```
+
+Do not build the whole target system in one diff. The smallest reviewed milestone wins.
